As negotiated in the October 1994 US-DPRK Agreed Framework, the U.S. committed to provide 500,000 tons of oil annually until completion of two lightwater nuclear reactors that are less susceptible to proliferation than facilities that North Korea has previously operated, but "frozen" under the agreement.
In Fiscal Year 2003, North Korea received 40,200 metric tons of wheat from the United States valued roughly at $26 million.8 For the year 2000, North Korea's legal exports were estimated by the Central Intelligence Agency to amount to $708 million in goods -- most of which were to its neighbors China, Japan and South Korea.9 During the same period, imports (mostly from the same three nations) totaled $1.686 billion, leaving an estimated shortfall of $978 million.10 Many observers expect exports and imports to grow dramatically, in the absence of unforseen events, with no indication at this point of a narrowing trade gap in the immediate future.
For example, North/South Korea trade increased by about 57% in 2002 over 2001 levels and trade with Thailand increased some 67%.
