Media reports suggest that when Assistant Secretary of State, James A. Kelly, visited North Korea in October 2002, he asked that printing of the counterfeit bills be suspended.
Some of the bills are reportedly printed on machines stolen by the KGB from the U.S. mint after WWII and provided to North Korea by the USSR in the late 1980s (See: "DPRK Prints Super K Dollar Bills on Machine Provided by Former USSR KGB," Tokyo Forsight (in Japanese) 15 March-18 April 2003.)
Others are believed to be printed on equipment purchased by the DPRK in Europe in the 1990s.
Quality control is reportedly exercised by use of state of the art equipment designed to detect counterfeiting, reportedly also purchased in Europe.
